{
  "id": "u1-1-vowels",
  "day": "1.1 — 1. den",
  "title": "Czech vowels, length, and stress",
  "summary": "Build a reliable pronunciation foundation: five basic vowel qualities, short–long contrast, common vowel pairs, and first-syllable stress.",
  "estimatedMinutes": 22,
  "objectives": ["Read a, e, i/y, o, and u consistently", "Recognize long vowels marked with čárka or kroužek", "Place stress on the first syllable", "Connect written words with pictures and spoken Czech"],
  "sections": [
    {"heading": "Five basic vowel qualities", "body": "Czech spelling is much more predictable than English spelling. The letters i and y represent the same vowel sound, although they affect surrounding consonants differently in later lessons.", "examples": ["a: mapa, vlak", "e: pes, televize", "i/y: mobil, byt", "o: okno, pivo", "u: tužka, učitel"]},
    {"heading": "Short and long vowels", "body": "Vowel length is meaningful. Long vowels are normally written with an acute accent; ů is another spelling of long u. Hold a long vowel roughly twice as long as the corresponding short vowel.", "examples": ["byt — apartment / být — to be", "mapa / otázka", "u: úkol, ů: stůl"]},
    {"heading": "Vowel pairs and stress", "body": "Common written pairs combine predictably. Czech word stress normally falls on the first syllable, even when a word is long.", "examples": ["au: auto", "ou: houba", "aj: čaj", "ej: kolej", "STU-dent, TE-le-vi-ze"]}
  ],
